'''Chelpan Konstantin Fyodorovich''' ({{lang-ru|[[<U+0427><U+0435><U+043B><U+043F><U+0430><U+043D>, <U+041A><U+043E><U+043D><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+0442><U+0438><U+043D> <U+0424><U+0451><U+0434><U+043E><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+0447>]]}}) (27 May 1899 <U+2013> 10 May 1938) <U+2013> prominent Ukrainian-Soviet engineer of Greek background. Head of the Engineering Design Bureau of the [[Malyshev Factory|Kharkiv Locomotive Factory]], chief designer of the [[T-34|T-34 tank]] engine. Awarded the [[Order of Lenin]].  Politically repressed and executed under a mass persecution ordered by [[Joseph Stalin]]. [[Political rehabilitation|Politically rehabilitated]] after death.

== Early Life and Education ==

Born on May 24, 1899 in Cherdakly, [[Yekaterinoslav Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]] (now Kremenivka, [[Donetsk Oblast]], [[Ukraine]]),<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|last=<U+041B><U+0430><U+0432><U+0440><U+0438><U+043D><U+0435><U+043D><U+043A><U+043E>|first=<U+0415><U+0432><U+0433><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438><U+0439>|title=<U+0427><U+0435><U+043B><U+043F><U+0430><U+043D> <U+041A><U+043E><U+043D><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+0442><U+0438><U+043D> <U+0424><U+0435><U+0434><U+043E><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+0447>|url=http://donbass.name/2586-glavnyj-konstruktor-v-2.html|work=<U+0430><U+043B><U+043B><U+0435><U+044F> <U+0437><U+0432><U+0435><U+0437><U+0434>|accessdate=19 February 2012|language=Russian|month=01|year=2011}}</ref>  to Fyodor Myhailovich Chelpan and Elizaveta Khalangot.<ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite book|last=<U+0417><U+0430><U+0445><U+0430><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>|first=<U+0413>.<U+041C>.|title=<U+0416><U+0438><U+0437><U+043D><U+0435><U+043E><U+043F><U+0438><U+0441><U+0430><U+043D><U+0438><U+044F> <U+0437><U+043D><U+0430><U+043C><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438><U+0442><U+044B><U+0445> <U+0433><U+0440><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432> <U+0423><U+043A><U+0440><U+0430><U+0438><U+043D><U+044B>. <U+0414><U+0435><U+043B><U+043E> <U+041A><U+043E><U+043D><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+0442><U+0438><U+043D><U+0430>  <U+0427><U+0435><U+043B><U+043F><U+0430><U+043D><U+0430>|year=2001|publisher=<U+041C><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+0443><U+043F><U+043E><U+043B><U+044C> : <U+0417><U+0410><U+041E> <U+00AB><U+0413><U+0430><U+0437><U+0435><U+0442><U+0430> "<U+041F><U+0440><U+0438><U+0430><U+0437><U+043E><U+0432><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438><U+0439> <U+0440><U+0430><U+0431><U+043E><U+0447><U+0438><U+0439>|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=54<U+2013>85|language=Russian}}</ref>  Both parents were [[Greeks in Ukraine|Ukrainian Greeks]].<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
   
After graduating from Mariupol [[Realschule]] in 1919, took part it the [[Russian Civil War]].<ref name="ReferenceB"/> In 1924 graduated with honors from [[Kharkiv Polytechnic Institute|Kharkiv Technological Institute]] with a Major in Internal Combustion Engines.<ref name="ReferenceB"/><ref name="ReferenceC">{{cite web|last=<U+0414><U+0436><U+0443><U+0445><U+0430>|first=<U+0418>.<U+0413>.|title=<U+0427><U+0435><U+043B><U+043F><U+0430><U+043D> <U+041A>.<U+0424>.|url=http://www.greek-martirolog.ru/dbm_person/persona.php?id=5322965_199aa|work=<U+0413><U+0420><U+0415><U+0427><U+0415><U+0421><U+041A><U+0418><U+0419> <U+041C><U+0410><U+0420><U+0422><U+0418><U+0420><U+041E><U+041B><U+041E><U+0413>|accessdate=19 February 2012|language=Russian}}</ref>  

== Career ==

From 1924 to 1937 worked at the [[Malyshev Factory|Kharkiv Locomotive Factory]]<ref name="ReferenceC"/>  as a Designer, Head of the Diesel Department, Lead Designer, and Head of the Engineering Design Bureau.<ref>{{cite book|last=<U+0418><U+0431><U+0440><U+0430><U+0433><U+0438><U+043C><U+043E><U+0432>|first=<U+0414><U+0430><U+043D><U+0438><U+044F><U+043B>|title=<U+041F><U+0440><U+043E><U+0442><U+0438><U+0432><U+043E><U+0431><U+043E><U+0440><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E>: <U+0414><U+043E><U+043A><U+0443><U+043C><U+0435><U+043D><U+0442><U+0430><U+043B><U+044C><U+043D><U+0430><U+044F> <U+043F><U+043E><U+0432><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+044C>|year=1989|publisher=<U+0414><U+041E><U+0421><U+0410><U+0410><U+0424> <U+0421><U+0421><U+0421><U+0420>|isbn=5703002001|url=http://books.google.com.ua/books?ei=QuhAT5_SMMjBtAay_rHGBA&hl=uk&id=zk19AAAAIAAJ&dq|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=59|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=<U+0414><U+0436><U+0443><U+0445><U+0430>|first=<U+0418><U+0432><U+0430><U+043D>|title=<U+0413><U+0440><U+0435><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430><U+044F> <U+043E><U+043F><U+0435><U+0440><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+044F>: <U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F> <U+0440><U+0435><U+043F><U+0440><U+0435><U+0441><U+0441><U+0438><U+0439> <U+043F><U+0440><U+043E><U+0442><U+0438><U+0432> <U+0433><U+0440><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432> <U+0432> <U+0421><U+0421><U+0421><U+0420>|year=2006|publisher=<U+0410><U+043B><U+0435><U+0442><U+0435><U+0439><U+044F>|isbn=5893298543|pages=408|url=http://books.google.com.ua/books?id=OH8iAQAAIAAJ&q|coauthors=<U+0410><U+0441><U+0441><U+043E><U+0446><U+0438><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+044F> <U+0433><U+0440><U+0435><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438><U+0445> <U+043E><U+0431><U+0449><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0435><U+043D><U+043D><U+044B><U+0445> <U+043E><U+0431><U+044A><U+0435><U+0434><U+0438><U+043D><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438><U+0439> <U+0420><U+043E><U+0441><U+0441><U+0438><U+0438>|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=50|language=Russian}}</ref>  In 1928-1929 had practical training in Germany, Switzerland, and the UK.<ref name="ReferenceB"/> 

Konstantin Chelpan was the head designer of the famous [[T-34|T-34 tank]] diesel engine [[Diesel model V-2|V-2]],<ref>{{cite book|last=<U+041A><U+043E><U+0441><U+0442><U+044E><U+0447><U+0435><U+043D><U+043A><U+043E>|first=<U+0421><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+0438><U+0441><U+043B><U+0430><U+0432>|title=<U+041A><U+0430><U+043A> <U+0441><U+043E><U+0437><U+0434><U+0430><U+0432><U+0430><U+043B><U+0430><U+0441><U+044C> <U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430><U+044F> <U+043C><U+043E><U+0449><U+044C> <U+0421><U+043E><U+0432><U+0435><U+0442><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E><U+0433><U+043E> <U+0421><U+043E><U+044E><U+0437><U+0430>, <U+041A><U+043D><U+0438><U+0433><U+0430> 1|year=2004|publisher=<U+0410><U+0421><U+0422>|isbn=5170243960|pages=574|url=http://books.google.com.ua/books?id=Y3_fAAAAMAAJ&q|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=204, 208|language=Russian}}</ref>  for which he was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]].<ref>{{cite book|last=<U+0411><U+0423><U+0413><U+0410><U+0419>|first=<U+041D><U+0418><U+041A><U+041E><U+041B><U+0410><U+0419>|title=<U+041E><U+0431><U+044F><U+0437><U+0430><U+0442><U+044C> <U+041D><U+041A><U+0412><U+0414> <U+0421><U+0421><U+0421><U+0420> ... <U+0432><U+044B><U+0441><U+0435><U+043B><U+0438><U+0442><U+044C> <U+0433><U+0440><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432>|year=1999|publisher=<U+0418><U+041D><U+0421><U+0410><U+041D>|pages=159|url=http://books.google.com.ua/books?id=He9LAAAAMAAJ&q|coauthors=<U+041A><U+041E><U+0426><U+041E><U+041D><U+0418><U+0421>, <U+0410><U+041D><U+0410><U+0422><U+041E><U+041B><U+0418><U+0419>|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=164|language=Russian}}</ref>  The engine consisted of lightweight aluminum alloy,<ref>{{cite book|last=Suzuki|first=Takashi|title=The romance of engines|year=1997|publisher=SAE|isbn=1560919116|pages=468|url=http://books.google.com.ua/books/about/The_romance_of_engines.html?id=F7alJT8YtaQC&redir_esc=y|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=206|language=English}}</ref>  and was the first case of a diesel engine being used in a tank,<ref>{{cite book|title=<U+041E><U+0442><U+0435><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0435><U+043D><U+043D><U+044B><U+0435> <U+0430><U+0440><U+0445><U+0438><U+0432><U+044B>, <U+0412><U+044B><U+043F><U+0443><U+0441><U+043A> 1|year=2001|publisher=<U+041E><U+0442><U+0435><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0435><U+043D><U+043D><U+044B><U+0435> <U+0430><U+0440><U+0445><U+0438><U+0432><U+044B>|url=http://books.google.com.ua/books?id=Vv0ZAAAAYAAJ&q|author=<U+041A><U+043E><U+043C><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435><U+0442> <U+043F><U+043E> <U+0434><U+0435><U+043B><U+0430><U+043C> <U+0430><U+0440><U+0445><U+0438><U+0432><U+043E><U+0432>. <U+041C><U+0438><U+043D><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+0440><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+043F><U+0435><U+0447><U+0430><U+0442><U+0438> <U+0438> <U+0438><U+043D><U+0444><U+043E><U+0440><U+043C><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+0438>|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=63|language=Russian}}</ref> which made it a groundbreaking weapon.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ziemke|first=Earl|title=Stalingrad to Berlin: The German Defeat in the East (Paper)|year=2002|publisher=Government Printing Office|isbn=0160019621|pages=561|url=http://books.google.com.ua/books/about/Stalingrad_to_Berlin_The_German_Defeat_i.html?id=Pr6HhrecbZ8C&redir_esc=y|accessdate=19 February 2012|page=27|language=English}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceD">{{cite web|title=<U+0421><U+0442><U+0430><U+043B><U+0438><U+043D><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438><U+0439> "<U+0433><U+0440><U+0435><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438><U+0439> <U+0437><U+0430><U+0433><U+043E><U+0432><U+043E><U+0440>"|url=http://www.greekgazeta.ru/archives/nomer03/articles/28.shtml|work=<U+0413><U+0420><U+0415><U+041A><U+0418> <U+0412> <U+0420><U+041E><U+0421><U+0421><U+0418><U+0418>|publisher=<U+0413><U+0420><U+0415><U+0427><U+0415><U+0421><U+041A><U+0410><U+042F> <U+0413><U+0410><U+0417><U+0415><U+0422><U+0410>|accessdate=19 February 2012|language=Russian}}</ref>     

From [[1927]] was a senior lecturer at [[Kharkiv Polytechnic Institute|Kharkiv Technological Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|last=<U+041F><U+0430><U+0432><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>|first=<U+0413>. <U+0412>.|title=<U+0427><U+0435><U+043B><U+043F><U+0430><U+043D> <U+041A><U+043E><U+043D><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+0442><U+0438><U+043D> <U+0424><U+0435><U+0434><U+043E><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+0447>|url=http://library.kpi.kharkov.ua/PREPODAVATELY/PR_%D7.html|work=<U+0418><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F> <U+0425><U+0430><U+0440><U+044C><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E><U+0433><U+043E> <U+0442><U+0435><U+0445><U+043D><U+043E><U+043B><U+043E><U+0433><U+0438><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E><U+0433><U+043E> <U+0438><U+043D><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+0442><U+0443><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0432> <U+043B><U+0438><U+0446><U+0430><U+0445> 1885-1930|accessdate=19 February 2012|language=Russian}}</ref>

== Arrest and Death ==

Konstantin Chelpan was arrested on December 15, 1937 during the first days of [[Greek Operation of NKVD]].<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref name="ReferenceB"/><ref name="ReferenceD"/>  He was charged with leading a Greek nationalist contra-revolutionary organization, as well as consipring to sabotage the [[Malyshev Factory|Kharkiv Locomotive Factory]].<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref name="ReferenceD"/>  After being interrogated and tortured he confessed of being a spy.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>  On February 4, 1938 he was sentenced to [[execution by shooting]].<ref name="ReferenceB"/><ref name="ReferenceC"/><ref name="ReferenceD"/>  The sentence was carried out in  [[Kharkiv]] prison on March 10, 1938<ref name="ReferenceB"/>  and covered up.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>  In a few years his wife received a death certificate, indicating that Konstantin Chelpan Died on May 16, 1942 from [[Heart failure|congestive heart failure]].<ref name="ReferenceA"/> 

On August 6, 1956, Konstantin Chelpan was [[Political rehabilitation|politically rehabilitated]] by the [[Military Collegium of the Supreme Court of the USSR]].<ref name="ReferenceB"/><ref name="ReferenceC"/>  However only in 1988 his true cause of death was revealed.<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref name="ReferenceD"/>

== Commemoration ==
* In 1994 one of the streets in the village of Cherdakly was named after Konstantin Chelpan.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>
* In 2000 a book entitled ''Life story of famous Ukrainian Greeks. The case of Konstantin Chelpan'' by G. Zakharova was published.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>
* In 2001 a [[commemorative plaque]] was placed on the house, where Konstantin Chelpan had spent his last years.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>

